Time to move on.

replies.commentText: Chandler Eade, you're a bit short on facts to be so dismissive. 1. There was no invasion. It's an odd day to celebrate for any Australians. For aboriginal people it marks an invasion. For non-aboriginal australians it's the day a penal colony was established. The first fleet consisted of six convict transports, 3 supply ships and 2 navy escorts; with 582 male, 193 female and 14 child convicts, with 348 others (ships crew, marines and admin). 48 died and 28 were born en-route. The colony came close to starving in its early years. Many of the local aboriginal people died around the same time of smallpox. 
The history is complex and dark, but not without flashes of hope. It is a different history from, say, South Africa or the USA, and to equate them with each other is to disdain the unique suffering of them all. 26 January 1788 was not a happy day for anyone, but something survived and grew, and it is in that shared survival and growth that there is perhaps some scope for all of us to reflect soberly on our shared past, present state and future improvement.

commentThread.commentText: Wow i learnt something new today. Respect to the aboriginal people.

This is emotive but poorly thought out. If we go down the route that 'History is offensive' we will never celebrate anything.

The majority of celebrations of national days, liberations, famous battles etc. Are about one side triumphing over another.

None of the people in this video were alive to feel the grievances of the arrival of the British, nor were their grandparents.

But they were all born in modern Australia, which protects the rights of its citizens, outlaws discrimination and actively promotes and celebrates the cultural heritage of all its people.

Modern Australia day is as much a celebration of Australians as it is of Australia.

So, whilst the emotion is understandable, it's illogical. Move forwards - life is better that way.

I can't believe half of you people in the comments section. Honestly saying "It's ancient history, move on" is incredibly offensive. For starters, Captain Cook discovered Australia in 1770 - thats only 246 years ago. Australia became a federation in 1901 - that's 115 years ago. The White Australian Policy (A policy which attempted to literally breed the black out of Indigenous Australians) was created in 1901 and wasn't COMPLETELY dismantled until 1973 - thats only 43 years ago. Majority of these people don't know their grandparents and some wouldn't know their parents. To this day, their are Indigenous Australian's who don't know their culture, who don't know where they came from and are unable to find out because their was no documentation. They are known as the Stolen Generation. They were treated horribly. Imagine yourself in that situation, can you blame them for not liking Australia Day? Can you blame them for the way they feel? So the next time you say "It's ancient history, move on" get your facts straight. It's modern history and still affects Indigenous Australians today.

The Indigenous people would have been ok with sharing* the land, but the Europeans classed the Indigenous people as fauna and it was legal to kill them because of the classification. The VCAA states, "There was also a belief that Aborigines were dying out and incapable of voting. To Aborigines, this meant that their citizenship status was equivalent to ‘flora and fauna'."

The myth that the Constitution included a reference to the Aboriginal people under a 'flora and fauna' section is entirely erroneous. +chaiTV I'm a direct descendent of Tasmanian Aboriginals. I've just spent the past year of my life doing aboriginal studies and my family has published about three books on the matter. Trust me, I'm plenty educated on the matter. It is quite literally my family history. Having advanced technology and medicine means nothing. It's great for us because it's what we were raised with, we adapted to living in a life filled with technological and medicinal advancements. However, the Aboriginal people adapted to life without those advancements and lived just fine without them. For 40, 000 years to be exact. They were more aware and cautious of the dangers of their environments because they knew that they couldn't combat poisons. They had their own methods of surviving off the land and it worked extremely well for them. And you think they didn't work out how to set a bone? You think they didn't have their own medicines? Not all medicine needs to come from artificial chemicals, you know that right? Sure, they probably had their tough times, just like people today do, but just because you couldn't possibly imagine surviving without technology and advanced medicine, it doesn't mean that they had a tough time managing it (again with the arrogance of thinking you're somehow better or your life is somehow more fulfilled because you had things they didn't). They suffered far more hardship when the ships came in then they ever did before the Europeans came. And all these advancements, whilst they did make improvements and bring to life marvellous things, they also came with their own set of problems. You're holding onto the belief that the European lifestyle was somehow better or more fulfilling because of their advancements, when really the Aboriginal people led very fulfilling lives. They lived their own way but Europeans were so arrogant to believe that their way was the right way. There is no right way to live. You can live in technological luxury or live off of the land. The only thing that determines which is better than the other is perception. There is more to life than advancing nations. Whilst advanced technology and medicine is fantastic, it isn't required to lived, and it certainly isn't some stamp of superiority.

@Iron Khaleesi Sounds to me like you want it both ways. Well, you can't. When Aboriginal people wandered down to Tas, they couldn't get back once the sea level rose. Stranded in Tasmania during the ice age, and here you are  thinking they lived "just fine". Just because they survived the ice age in Tas, doesn't mean they were "just fine". Not having sailing boat technology meant they were stuck. Isolated from their mainland families for thousands of years meant they missed out on the few things that mainlanders did invent such as boomerang and other tools.  Look, I respect the lengthy survival time of these people, and their general connection with the land and nature. But their small numbers suggests high mortality and limited life.  Their "land management" is way overhyped in my opinion. They would burn huge areas of bush just to attract roos who would come to feed on the seeds left over etc. It was clunky inefficient and only sustainable because of their low numbers in this huge land. They had no scalable system, not even close. What they did have was a huge piece of Earth all to themselves. Lucky. Okay, so you may put all the good things about their culture  into a bottle, but don't hold that up as the complete story. Yes of course there was admirable harmonic qualities, but don't underestimate the fight for survival that took up most of their day. Only a few thousand people in Tas... no wonder their impact on the environment was low. Scale the population up and there's no way on Earth that Indigenous methods would work in terms of feeding and sustaining large numbers. Let's enjoy the stories of pre-technology times, and acknowledge the wrongs and crimes of some settlers such as child abduction and mishandling of land. But you'll never convince me that 40,000 years means they had 40,000 years of peace, harmony and happiness. Aborigines were keen to trade for flour and tobacco and many other things. If they were "just fine" they would have said "no thanks" when given those new things.

And again, if you jad read my previous comments properly you would know that I jave already said I know nothing can be changed, but all I want to get through peoples heads is that what happened deserve to be acknowledged. And the Aboroginal people that lost their lives because of the invasion deserve to be commemorated. And you really think an apology was going to satiate the anger and sadness that people felt? If I came around and killed your parents for no good reason, then issued an formal apology once would you be happy with that? I didn't think so. When the apology was issued, Aboroginal people, including myself had hoped that it was just the first step towards a proper acknowledgement and commemoration of what happened. But the n nothing else happened. So of course people got pissed again.

+AnotherFastnet70 People seem to forget that this dodn't happen thousands of years ago. It was peoples parents and grand parents that suffered this. Some of the stolen generation are still alive today and hoping to find their real families.

Why demand we say sorry if that's not what you want ? That's plain ridiculous. There has been acknowledgement over and over again.....what do you actually want as it cannot merely be acknowledgement. Your people today are afforded health and education services over and above that of non indigenous Australians as well as a range of other services, such as job places, interest free loans etc The Australian taxpayer foots the bill so what else do you want ? A commemoration ? Then what after that ? It's impossible to please someone that simply refuses to ever be pleased.
c'mon guys Australia is still a young country racial segregation and discrimination only died down in like the 60's/70's

+Iron Khaleesi They were socialists in the true sense...the Europeans however were takers and 200 years later have been revealed as poor managers of the land for that short space of time...that's an undisputed fact.

+AnotherFastnet70 I haven't asked for an apology at all. I asked for commemoration every year, that's the only thing that will make Aboriginal people believe that we are truly sorry for what happened. Yes, they have benefits, and that's great. But throwing money at a problem and apologising once just to shut people up isn't going to appease anyone. The problem is that everyone seems to forget what happened. And they don't want that. They want to know that people understand the sacrifice our families had to suffer in order for Australian society to be the way it is today. And it'd be great if the last remaining Aboriginal communities were just left alone to live on their land rather than be moved around every couple years for mining. How is that too much to ask? And it's nothing but pessimism that makes you believe we would want more than that, and there's nothing I can do to fix that.

You may not have asked for an apology but you are only one person. Your people as a collective banged on for years about how the government should say sorry. John Howard refused to but when Kevin Rudd did it's not enough. What a complete waste of time, effort and money. So what type of commemoration are you speaking of ? I have no problem with Aboriginal communities living anywhere but if they want to live how they always did then be self sufficient and don't put the hand out when it suits. You can't have it both ways. You may call it pessimism but I call it realism.

+AnotherFastnet70 That's a generalisation. But either way they had every right to demand an apology, but they had hoped that the apology would lead to something more. Because there is a difference between them and the handful of Aboroginal people who take advantage of the system.

+chaiTV I feel like I'm beating my head against the brick wall now. The first half of your comment I've already discussed with you, and I'm about to retype everything just for you. I never said there was frequent communication between communities. But when they did communicate with each other it was through dance and paintings. Which were and still are beautiful forms of communication if you ever get to watch it happen. Different dialects doesn't suggest conflict nor isolation. Each community had several different languages. You keep thinking that they thought of communication the same way Europeans did. If an Elder of the community died than quite often they ceased to use the dialect that the Elder most commonly used as a sign of respect. Yes the communities lived apart. But that doesn't mean they were isolated. Each community had their own rules and were led by their own Elders. They lived and talked differently. That doesn't mean they never saw each other or that they hated each other. Yes, of course there would be conflict sometimes. Misunderstandings happen. People get angry. But there certainly wasn't conflict to the extent that there is today amongst people. They didn't just go around fighting each other whenever they crossed paths. And of course they had exceptional land management skills! Did you not read anything that I wrote about how they managed the land?? And so what if not all communities managed the land the same way?? There wasn't one right way to do it!! Many of them lived on different types of land. And who cares if they didn't all unite together to create one bi g nation?! Why does that matter?! They didn't care about creating technology or capitalism. They didn't care about making money. They just cared about their community. They were happy living the way they did. You're so arrogant to believe that living the Europeans way is the only way to be happy. Sure they were evolving a little slower, but so what? Was it hurting anyone? No. And everything in life is trial and error!!! That's how they came to understand the land they were living on!

+chaiTV And okay I jumped the gun a little on saying there was evidence of intentionally introduced diseases as I'm not %100 certain on that matter. But it's the only logical conclusion. Do you have any idea how many disease were introduced? You're telling me that every person on those boats just happened to be sick with every kind of European disease? Sure it may have been an accident in the beginning. But I find it extremely doubtful that it wasn't utilised to their advantage once they realised what had happened. Again, you only have to look at the sheer number of deaths in a short space of time and the number of diseases. And even if it were all unintentional, disease wasn't the only thing that happened to them, as I've said plenty of times before.

+AnotherFastnet70 Commemoration. Right. I'm not entirely certain of what the details would be. There are people out there who suffered enormously from what happened and I do believe that they should be the ones asked about what they would like included in the commemoration. But perhaps acknowledgments of the Nations that suffered most (especially the Tasmanian nations). Acknowledgements of the stolen genrations. Acknowledgments of the European families who suffered for trying to protect local Aboriginal nations and children. These at least, would be the main points that I would like to hear. But again, it's not entirely up to me obviously. I am a descendent of a Tasmanian Aboriginal community, but I am lucky enough to also be a descendant of a family who put their lives on the line trying to protect and hide Aboriginal children that were being taken away from their homes.

+Iron Khaleesi As far as I'm aware the stolen generation has been acknowledged. The land issues has also be acknowledged in a court of law. Haphazard record keeping from those times means individual acknowledgement is virtually impossible. This is not just a unique situation to this matter. Record keeping was poor across all walks of life back then. As I have previously stated the world was a much different place then. Maybe the families of people who were hanged will come out and say how corporal punishment was inhumane and seek compensation as well ? The families of convicts who had loved ones sent to the other side of the world, some of whom died on the journey, for stealing a loaf of bread or a blanket. Maybe they should also seek acknowledgement or some form of compensation as well ? Where does it ever end ?

+AnotherFastnet70 You're not listening to anything I'm saying. Or in this case not reading and understanding properly. I'm aware that acknowledgments and apologies have already been issued. But it happened once. Maybe twoce if we were lucky in some cases, and then money was thrown at it and it was swept under the rug. I'm asking for commemoration every year. Re-issuing apologies and acknowledgments. Perhaps even allowing Aboriginal communities to perform their own dances and ceremonies. Just something to show that what happened isn't some dark dirty secret that we're trying to get rid of. It's part of our history. And it should be treated as such. I don't have an opinion on the convict situation. Though funnily enough that's how part of my family ended up in Australia. But I assume you're just throwing that out their to try and come up with an excuse as to why we shouldn't commemorate the Aboriginal communities. And it's a pathetic excuse at that. I didn't ask for individual commemoration. I'm not stupid. I know you can't possibly track all that down. But it's not to hard to mention  them all as a whole. And I didn't ask for more compensation either.
